{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660009"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22642"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22642"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112747"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15589"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22642"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94781"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46324"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112747"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of chest pain after falling off a ladder at work. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as a painter and decorator. On examination, he appears uncomfortable but alert. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is visible swelling over the left chest wall. On palpation, there is a crackling sensation over the left chest wall. Percussion reveals hyperresonance at the left apex. Auscultation demonstrates reduced breath sounds at the left apex. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physical signs would be most apparent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dullness at the left lung base","Reduced breath sounds at the left apex","Tenderness on palpation over the sternum","Tenderness over the ninth and 10th left ribs","Surgical crepitus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has sustained thoracic trauma from a fall, and the CT scan shows multiple abnormalities including a left-sided pneumothorax, pleural fluid (likely haemothorax), and extensive subcutaneous emphysema over the left chest wall. The combination of these findings suggests significant thoracic injury with air leaking from the lung into both the pleural space and subcutaneous tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical crepitus\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as subcutaneous emphysema) would be the most apparent physical sign. This presents as a distinctive crackling or popping sensation felt when palpating the skin, caused by air trapped in the subcutaneous tissues. The extensive subcutaneous air visible on the CT scan would produce obvious crepitus over a large area of the chest wall, making it the most readily detectable sign on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced breath sounds at the left apex\u003C/strong\u003E would be present due to the pneumothorax, but this is a more subtle finding requiring careful auscultation. While important diagnostically, it would not be as immediately apparent as the crepitus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDullness at the left lung base\u003C/strong\u003E might be expected from the pleural fluid collection seen on CT. However, the amount of fluid appears relatively small and may not produce significant dullness to percussion, particularly if the patient is examined sitting upright.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETenderness on palpation over the sternum\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ETenderness over the ninth and 10th left ribs\u003C/strong\u003E are not supported by the CT findings, which show no evidence of bony injury. While soft tissue injury might cause some tenderness, this would be less prominent than the crepitus and not specific to these anatomical locations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of surgical crepitus in a trauma patient should always raise suspicion for underlying pneumothorax or injury to air-containing structures. In this case, the extensive subcutaneous emphysema visible on CT correlates with a finding that would be immediately obvious on physical examination, even to a less experienced clinician.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subcutaneous emphysema (surgical crepitus) is a palpable crackling sensation caused by air trapped in subcutaneous tissues.","In trauma patients, subcutaneous emphysema often indicates underlying pneumothorax or injury to air-containing structures.","Physical examination findings in pneumothorax include reduced breath sounds, hyperresonance to percussion, and subcutaneous emphysema if air tracks into soft tissues."],"references":["Tran J, Haussner W, Shah K. Traumatic Pneumothorax: A Review of Current Diagnostic Practices And Evolving Management. J Emerg Med. 2021; 61:517-28.","D\u0027Souza D, Rizi F, Walizai T, et al. Subcutaneous emphysema. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 05 Sep 2025) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-4038"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94781"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22642"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22016"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22016"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tzaBqINJRfiG638ywEEqAywCKZ5REe.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tzaBqINJRfiG638ywEEqAywCKZ5REe.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":563,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94781"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-05T11:15:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-05T11:16:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15589"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112747"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes